summary:
In this paper we prove Modica type estimates for the following overdetermined $p$-Laplace problem \begin{equation*}
  \begin{cases}
  \mathrm{div} \left(|\nabla u|^{p-2}\nabla u\right)+f(u) =0& \mbox{in $Î©$, }
  u>0 &\mbox{in $Î©$, }
  u=0 &\mbox{on $\partialÎ©$, }
  \partial_Î½ u=-Îº&\mbox{on $\partialÎ©$, }
  \end{cases} \end{equation*} where $1<p<+\infty$, $f\in C^1(\mathbb{R})$, $Î©\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ ($n\geq 2$) is a $C^1$ domain (bounded or unbounded), $Î½$ is the exterior unit normal of $\partial Î©$ and $Îº\geq 0$ is a constant. Based on Modica type estimates, we obtain rigidity results for bounded solutions. In particular, we prove that if there exists a nonpositive primitive $F$ of $f$ satisfying $F(0)\geq -(p-1)Îº^p / p$ (for $p>2$ we also assume that if $F(u_0)=0$, $F(u)=O(|u-u_0|^p)$ as $u\rightarrow u_0$), then either the mean curvature of $\partial Î©$ is strictly negative or $Î©$ is a half-space.
